					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Is It Possible to Start Out Poor in This Country, Work Hard and Become Well-Off?</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Michael Gonchar			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-12-12T10:00:31+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">December 12, 2014 5:00 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">December 12, 2014 5:00 am</span>		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/11/business/Polljp-LN/Polljp-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/11/business/Polljp-LN/Polljp-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/11/business/Polljp-LN/Polljp-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003299203" width="592" height="398" alt="The public has a bleaker view of upward mobility than it did after the 2008 financial crisis, according to a New York Times poll, despite an improving economy and an increase in jobs. &lt;a href=&quot;//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/10/many-feel-the-american-dream-is-out-of-reach-poll-shows/&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="398"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The public has a bleaker view of upward mobility than it did after the 2008 financial crisis, according to a New York Times poll, despite an improving economy and an increase in jobs. <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/10/many-feel-the-american-dream-is-out-of-reach-poll-shows/">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Cheryl Senter for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/12/12/is-it-possible-to-start-out-poor-in-this-country-work-hard-and-become-well-off/" data-title="Is It Possible to Start Out Poor in This Country, Work Hard and Become Well-Off?" data-description="Do you believe that the United States is the &quot;land of opportunity&quot;? Do you think the American dream, however you define it, is alive and well?">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w151 right module">
<div class="entry"><a title="See all Student Opinion" href="/category/student-opinion/"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_student-opinion151.png" alt="Student Opinion - The Learning Network" /></a><a title="See all Student Opinion" href="/category/student-opinion/"><img class="w35 right" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_student-opinion35.png" alt="Student Opinion - The Learning Network" /></a></p>
<p class="summary">Questions about issues in the news for students 13 and older.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a title="See all Student Opinion" href="/category/student-opinion/">See all Student Opinion Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A recent New York Times poll determined that the public is more pessimistic than it was after the 2008 financial crisis that it is possible to go from being poor to rich in this country. We&#8217;re curious what students think?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Is it possible to start out poor, work hard and become well-off? How possible? And do you think it is getting easier or harder than it used to be?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-153352"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/10/many-feel-the-american-dream-is-out-of-reach-poll-shows/">&#8220;Many Feel the American Dream Is Out of Reach, Poll Shows,&#8221;</a> Andrew Ross Sorkin and Megan Thee-Brenan write:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
Despite an improving economy and jobs picture, the public is more pessimistic than it was after the 2008 financial crisis that it is possible to work hard and become rich, according to a New York Times poll.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The poll, which explored Americansâ opinions on a wide range of economic and financial issues, found that only 64 percent of respondents said they still believed in the American dream, the lowest result in roughly two decades. Even near the depth of the financial crisis in early 2009, 72 percent of Americans still believed that hard work could result in riches.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThings have changed a lot,â Michael Herdmann, a 54-year-old retired public works employee from Fairview Park, Ohio, said in a follow-up interview. âThe decks have been stacked against not only the lower class but also the lower middle class.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe modern-day politician has lost track of why the welfare programs were put in place,â he added. âThey donât understand that part of the reason we help the poor to buy food was also to help fund the farmers. They have systemically reduced most of what was there to help the poor.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The significant drop in faith comes as the nation added 321,000 jobs last month and average hourly earnings for ordinary workers increased much more than expected. The economy is also being buoyed by a drop in oil prices, putting more money in the pockets of average Americans as the holiday season approaches.
</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Students:</strong> Read the entire article, then tell us &#8230;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; Is it possible to start out poor in this country, work hard and become well-off? How possible? And do you think it is getting easier or harder than it used to be?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; Do you believe that the United States is the &#8220;land of opportunity&#8221;? Do you think the American dream, however you define it, is alive and well?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; How much of an advantage do you think young people from wealthy families have over young people from poor families when it comes to getting ahead in this country?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; How optimistic are you about getting a good job and living comfortably when you get older?</p>
<hr />
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Students 13 and older</strong> are invited to comment below. Please use only your <strong>first name.</strong> For <a href="//www.nytimes.com/ref/membercenter/help/privacysummary.html">privacy policy</a> reasons, we will not publish student comments that include a last name.</p>
	</div>
