			<span class="comment-author">Brenna</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-2100044" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">December 12, 2014</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">12:50 pm</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>I think it is still possible to start out poor in this country, work hard and become well off. However, I also think it is getting less and less possible as time goes on. Although there are more jobs being added to the market, it is still fairly difficult to find a good paying job with work hours that will not interfere with other necessary aspects of your life. I think it is harder now than it was in the past to pick up a job, start saving money, and buy the stereotypical big house with nice furniture. It can be done, but most of the time this financial security does not come until citizens are much older, if it ever comes at all.<br />
     I believe the United States could be considered the &#8220;land of opportunity.&#8221; We do have many jobs to choose from, and a lot of potential for people to develop. I also think the American dream is still alive, but at a much lower standard. It is becoming increasingly harder to find one of those model families with a happy couple, two children, a large house, fancy furniture, and the newest cars and technology. There are way more obstacles and distractions today than there were even ten years ago. People are making up their own American dream, though, where they come here and make a famous name for themselves, however long it lasts.<br />
     I think young people from wealthy families have a better chance of getting ahead in this country than young people from poor families. Wealthier people have names that are readily known in their community, sometimes even nationwide. This gives those young people an advantage to get better opportunities when it comes to colleges and careers. Of course, with enough motivation and effort, a poor person could get ahead in this country as much as anyone else. Still, wealthier people with well-known names are more likely to carry on the family tradition of being ahead.<br />
     I am pretty optimistic about getting a good job and living comfortably when I am older. Although I do not plan on going to a four-year university, I will be content on the money I make. I want to pursue a career in the medical field, which is very stable. I believe that I will be able to live comfortably when I am older, especially since money is not the most important thing in my life.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment alt" id="comment-2100049">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Joshua</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-2100049" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">December 12, 2014</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">12:55 pm</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>1. I believe that it is possible to start out poor in this country, work hard and become well off. I think it is possible through higher education like honors courses, and college. I think it is getting harder than it used to be as many more people are trying to do this, which is making them do literally anything to get there, including back stabbing, cheating, lying, and ruining others carries just to try to get there. Everyone scratching and clawing to get to the top.</p>
<p>2. I do believe the USA is the land of opportunity, because these options are not aloud in other places. I think the American Dream is different for each of us and is alive and well.</p>
<p>3. I think wealth young people have way more of an advantage than others. They can just pay their way to almost anywhere.</p>
<p>4. I guess you could say i am optimistic on my outlook of how it would be.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment" id="comment-2100057">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Kaela</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-2100057" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">December 12, 2014</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">1:00 pm</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>-I do believe that it is still possible for people to start out poor, work hard and then live comfortably; but, people rising up like that doesn&#8217;t happen very often anymore. It is getting harder and harder to be able to rise up like this. Maybe people have just given up hope of rising up, so they stick with what they have. It is definitely possible for someone to work their way out of the lower class, but it is more difficult than just finding a good paying job now.<br />
-America is still the land of opportunity, just not job opportunities. People in the lower class have little time on their hands to go to college, because they are working to be able to keep a roof over their heads. That makes it even more difficult to get a job when everyone is looking for someone with a college degree. The American dream is still alive but I believe that it is slowly looking more and more like just a dream to most people. There are plenty of opportunities out there we just have to work hard enough to be able to reach them.<br />
-In my opinion, young people from rich families will have a lot more opportunities to get ahead in this country. They have money and that is what they need to get everything they need to be successful. They can pay for a good college, and, if they get into the right field, can help get a better job. Young people from poor families are usually hard workers. They realize that nothing is going to be given to them; therefore, they fight their way to the top. It is hard to move up that way and a lot them will not make it. Young rich people don&#8217;t have to fight as hard and things will be close by them. So yes, it is easier for a young rich person.<br />
-Coming from a poorer family, I don&#8217;t think that I am going to be in the upper class one day. Being in the middle class is more reasonable for me. But there are a lot of opportunities out their that our parents didn&#8217;t have. Things like the early college program, that will help you get ahead in your education without having to pay. I have high hopes that I will be able to live comfortably in the middle class when I get older, but I don&#8217;t think it will be easy to make it there.</p>

		</div>
